\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. B. vulgaris} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl. }222 (1753). Annual to perennial up to 200 cm. Basal leaves ovate-cordate to rhombic-cuneate; cauline leaves rhombic to lanceolate. Inflorescence dense, becoming interrupted towards the base in fruit, ebracteate at least in the upper ½ . Receptacle pelviform; segments not more than 3 mm in fruit, incurved. Stigmas usually 2.{\i  S. & W. Europe northwards to c.} 59°{\i  N. in W. Sweden; cultivated throughout most of Europe, and occasionally naturalized.} Al Az Be Bl Br Bu Co Cr Da Ga Ge Gr Hb Ho Hs It Ju Lu Sa Si Su Tu.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  vulgaris} (subsp. {\i cicla} (L.) Arcangeli): Usually biennial. Stem up to 200 cm, erect; root swollen; leaves up to 20 cm; cymes 2- to 8-flowered. 2n = 18.{\i  Widely cultivated, some cultivars for sugar} ({\i Sugar-beet}),{\i  others for the edible leaf} ({\i Spinach-beet, Chard}), {\i hypocotyl and root} ({\i Beetroot}),{\i  others for fodder; often persisting as a casual and occasionally naturalized}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp.{\b  maritima} (L.) Arcangeli,{\i  Comp. Fl. Ital.} 593 (1882) ({\i B. maritima }L., {\i B. perennis} (L.) Freyn, {\i ?B. atriplicifolia} Rouy): Annual (especially in S. Europe) to perennial. Stem up to 80 cm, procumbent to erect, root usually not swollen; leaves up to 10 cm; cymes 1- to 3-flowered. 2n = 18.{\i  Coasts of S. & W. Europe, and as a weed inland in S. Europe}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 The many cultivars of subsp. ({\b a}) have sometimes been given subspecific or varietal rank.
