\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 3.              Chenopodium}                L.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By †J.P.M. Brenan (Ed.1) revised by J.R. Akeroyd (Ed.2)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Annual, rarely perennial herbs, glabrous, pubescent, glandular or farinose. Leaves alternate, flat. Flowers hermaphrodite and female, usually in cymes, variously arranged. Bracteoles absent. Perianth-segments 2-5, more or less unaltered in fruit, rarely becoming fleshy; stamens 1-5; stigmas 2(-5). Seeds usually horizontal.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Most species grow in man-made habitats and it is often impossible to decide whether they fall into the category of casual, established alien or native in any particular country.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 To see the markings on the testa, which are taxonomically important, the skin-like pericarp which closely invests the ripe seed must be removed; a magnification of × 40 is required.
